Fig. 16
 shows the transmission spectra of the sample CSV-1-450, CSV-2-450, CSV-3-450, CSV-1-550, CSV-2-550, and CSV-3-550 at 20 °C and 120 °C, respectively. The values of Tsol, Tlum and ΔTsol are listed in Table I. It was observed that all samples had visible transmittance in the range of 42.940 %–64.665 %, which indicated that these samples had a relatively high visible transmittance. Additionally, when the water bath time was fixed, the annealed samples at 550 °C had higher solar modulating ability compared with those at 450 °C. To our knowledge, the crystallinity and the corresponding surface electron density for VO2 will increase as the annealing temperature increases. This result may change the local surface plasmon resonance (LSPR), which can adjust the thermochromic properties of the composites [56]. Notably, the samples of CSV-1-450, CSV-2-450 and CSV-2-550 show negative values of ΔTsol, yet this is not an erroneous result. As the temperature increased to 120 °C, all annealed samples have undergone MIT. Of these, the transmittance in the range from visible region to 1100 nm for samples CSV-1-450, CSV-2-450 and CSV-2-550 at 120 °C was significantly higher than that at 20 °C (in Fig. 16(a), (b) and (e)). This result is attributed to the high solar occupancy for the three samples in this wavelength range, and then the solar modulation capacity in above region markedly reduces, resulting in negative values of ΔTsol (from 300 to 2500 nm). The same situation has been observed in previous literature [63]. Overall, the sample of CSV-3-550 had the optimal solar modulating ability (ΔTsol = 2.24 %) and the optimal luminous transmittance (Tlum = 64.665 %, Tlum = (Tlum,20°C − Tlum,120°C) / 2), which means that this sample obtained through the water bath time of 3 h and the annealing temperature of 550 °C has the best thermochromic performances. The Tlum and ΔTsol of VO2 films in published reports are presented in Table 2. Compared with former works (in Table 2), negative solar modulation rates were observed for ΔTsol of CSV-1-450, CSV-2-450 and CSV-2-550 in this work (in Table 1
), and the results for positive solar modulation rates were also lower than the available literature results. Additionally, the Tlum values of the samples in this work were comparable to those in the existing literatures. The ΔTsol and Tlum values of the samples almost increased with the increasing of the annealing temperature, which exhibited a balance between ΔTsol and Tlum besides the fluorescence properties and abnormal Tc.
